{{EngvarB|date=May 2013}} {{Infobox person | name = Crosaire | birth_name = John Derek Crozier | birth_date = {{Birth date|1917|11|12}} | birth_place = [[Belfast]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|2010|4|3|1917|11|12}} | death_place = | nationality = [[Ireland|Irish]] | occupation = Cricketer }} '''John Derek Crozier''' (12 November 1917 – 3 April 2010), under the pseudonym '''"Crosaire"''', was the compiler of the "''[[The Irish Times|Irish Times]]'' crossword" from its inception in 1943 until his death.<ref name="obit">{{Cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/obituaries/2010/0410/1224268029901.html|title=A riddler wrapped up in an enigma (5,7)|date=10 April 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|accessdate=7 June 2010}}</ref> As he was the sole compiler for 68 years,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/magazine/2011/1022/1224306043431.html |title=Carrying the Crossaire |work=The Irish Times |accessdate=2012-02-16}}</ref> the crossword itself became known as "the Crosaire" by [[metonymy]]. It is a [[cryptic crossword]], in contrast to the "Simplex crossword" which soon came to be published alongside it. Crozier's pseudonym "Crosaire" is a play on his own surname and ''crosaire'', the Irish for "crossroads".<ref name="tribute"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://focal.ie/Search.aspx?term=crosaire|title=crosaire|work=[[Focal (lexicographical website)|Focal]]|accessdate=7 June 2010}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|The Irish for "crossword" is the [[calque]] ''crosfhocal''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://focal.ie/Search.aspx?term=crossword|title=crossword|work=[[Focal (lexicographical website)|Focal]]|accessdate=7 June 2010}}</ref>|group="fn"}}
He retained an idiosyncratic approach to compilation; his crosswords never came to conform to the standards developed in Britain by "[[Derrick Somerset Macnutt|Ximenes]]". The day he died saw puzzle No 14,120 published;<ref name="tribute" /> ''The Irish Times'' crossword editor estimated there were a year's worth of his puzzles remaining to be published.<ref name="duncan">{{Cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2010/0407/breaking29.html|title='Irish Times' crossword compiler dies|last=Duncan|first=Pamela|date=7 April 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|accessdate=7 June 2010}}</ref>
He was born in Dublin and educated at Castle Park [[Preparatory school (UK)|preparatory school]] in [[Dalkey]] and [[Repton School]] in England.<ref name="obit" /> He graduated from [[Trinity College, Dublin]] in 1940.<ref name="tribute">{{Cite news|title=Derek Crozier 1917–2010|last=Kernan|first=Lorna|author2=Sarah Crushell |author3=Irene Stevenson |date=29 April 2010|work=The Irish Times|page=3, Supplement "40 Crosswords Celebrating the work of Derek Crozier"}}</ref> He worked in administration at the [[Guinness Brewery]] in [[St. James's Gate]].<ref name="tribute" /> He was introduced to editor [[Bertie Smyllie]] at an ''Irish Times'' party in a Dublin pub on Christmas Eve 1942, where he mentioned his hobby of compiling crosswords.<ref name="tribute" /> Smyllie commissioned him and the first ''Crosaire'' was printed on 13 March 1943.<ref name="tribute" /> Initially it appeared weekly on Saturdays, with Wednesdays added in 1950, Tuesdays in 1955, and a daily puzzle from 1982.<ref name="tribute" />
In 1948 Crozier emigrated to [[Southern Rhodesia]], now [[Zimbabwe]], to work as a tobacco and maize farmer in Sinoia, now [[Chinhoyi]].<ref name="tribute" /> He found farming difficult and the meagre income from his puzzles was important.<ref name="obit" /> In the [[Southern Rhodesian general election, 1962]], he stood for the [[United Federal Party]] in the [[Gwebi]] constituency, losing to [[Rhodesian Front]] candidate [[James Graham, 7th Duke of Montrose]]. From 1963 to 1989, he taught at St George's College in Salisbury, now [[Harare]].<ref name="tribute" /> His puzzles were often delivered to Ireland through visitors from abroad to avoid the vagaries of the Zimbabwe postal system.<ref name="tribute" /> He travelled to Dublin in 1993 for the 50th anniversary of his first puzzle, during which he appeared on ''[[The Late Late Show (Ireland)|The Late Late Show]]'' and at a forum for 400 fans chosen by lottery.<ref name="obit" /> He died at his home in [[Nyanga, Zimbabwe|Nyanga]], aged 92.<ref name="obit" /><ref name="tribute" /> A memorial service was held at St George's College, attended by his three sons.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2010/0410/1224268048623.html?via=rel|title=Memorial service in Zimbabwe for compiler of 'Irish Times' crosswords|last=Corcoran|first=Bill|date=10 April 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|accessdate=7 June 2010}}</ref>
[[Roy Earle]] (using the pseudonym ''Mac An Iarla'') took over as the compiler of the Crosaire following Crozier's death, with his crosswords appearing between Monday, 24 October 2011 and Saturday, 9 June 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/blogs/thecrosaireblog/2011/10/21/welcome-to-the-crosaire-blog/|title=Welcome to the Crosaire Blog|accessdate=2012-02-17 | work=The Irish Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Earle|first=Roy|title=Explanations: No. 14802 – Saturday, 9 Jun 2012|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/blogs/thecrosaireblog/2012/06/10/explanations-no-14802-saturday-9-jun-2012/|publisher=Irish Times|accessdate=4 January 2013}}</ref> The Crosaire has since been compiled by "Crossheir."
