'''Emilio Bozzi''' was an [[Italy|Italian]] businessman, known for his [[bicycle]] manufacturing company.<ref>{{cite web|title=Legnano: The Warrior’s Wheels|url=http://www.ebykr.com/2007/05/11/legnano-the-warriors-wheels/|accessdate=9 March 2016}}</ref> He established the '''Emilio Bozzi & Co.''' bicycle manufacturer in [[Milano]] (1908), the first model being the "Aurora".<ref>[http://www.classicrendezvous.com/Italy/Legnano/Legnano_history.htm The Legnano legend]</ref>
Also, he had the rights to the Turinese [[Frejus]] bicycle brand.  With the son of [[Franco Tosi]], who had some [[patent]]s from the English [[Wolseley Motors#Wolseley Italy or Wolsit|Wolsit]] brand, his company made the ''Ciclomotore Wolsit'' (1910–14), the rights to which was sold to [[NSU Motorenwerke AG]] (1932).

They renamed the company '''Legnano''' (the name of Bozzi's hometown) using a swordlifting legendary [[warrior]] ([[Alberto da Giussano]]) symbol painted by the cycler [[Alfredo Binda]], based on the [[Battle of Legnano]].  Along with Frejus they had immediate racing success with cyclists as [[Eberardo Pavesi]] (being the manager), [[Alfredo Binda]] (1922), [[Gino Bartali]] (1936), [[Fausto Coppi]] (1939), [[Ferdinand Kübler]] (1950)<ref>{{cite web|title=Frejus 1950 and 1951 Brochure|url=http://classicrendezvous.com/Italy/Frejus/Brochures_50_51.htm|accessdate=19 December 2012}}</ref>  and [[Ercole Baldini]] (1956) in the [[Giro d'Italia]], [[Tour de France]] and other races until 1965.  
The company also made [[moped]]s (1954–68), while the bicycle business was acquired by the main rival [[Bianchi (motorcycles)|Bianchi]].

