The U.S. '''Rubber Manufacturers Association''' ('''RMA'''), established in 1915 as the '''Rubber Club of America''', is a national [[trade group|trade]] and [[advocacy group]]<ref>[http://www.csub.edu/~mault/What%20Corporations%20Really%20Want%20From%20Government.pdf @CN:<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> of U.S. [[rubber tire]] manufacturers. The Rubber Manufacturers Association formed the '''Tire Industry Safety Council''' [[trade association]] in the United States in May 1969,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1338&dat=19691213&id=QWpYAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PfgDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4258,4057183&hl=en | title=Tire Industry Gets Rap in Safety-Measure Fuss | publisher=''Spokane Daily Chronicle'' | date=December 13, 1969 | accessdate=30 July 2016 | author=Anderson, Jack}}</ref><ref name="The Washingtion Times 2000">{{cite web | title=Tire recall focuses attention on usual question of underinflation | website=The Washingtion Times | date=August 25, 2000 | url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2000/aug/25/20000825-011848-7050r/ | accessdate=July 30, 2016}}</ref> which is based in Washington, D.C.<ref name="Pierson 2010">{{cite web | title=The State Of Studded Snow Tires | website=[[Chicago Tribune]] | date=March 11, 2010 | url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-10-23/travel/9410230088_1_permitted-restrictions-tires | accessdate=July 30, 2016}}</ref>
{{quote|RMA represents its members before federal, state and local government entities; develops [[safety standard]]s for passenger, light truck and commercial truck tires; advocates for environmentally and economically sound [[scrap tire]] management policies aggregates data pertaining to U.S. tire shipments; and, educates consumers about proper tire care, among other activities.|RMA - About Us}}
In 2015, [[government relations]] expert Anne Forristall Luke was nominated President and CEO of the RMA.<ref>[https://rma.org/content/rma-senior-management RMA Senior Management | Rubber Manufacturers Association<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
==Members== Members of the Rubber Manufacturers Association include:<ref>[https://rma.org/about-rma/member-directory Member Directory | Rubber Manufacturers Association<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> *[[Bridgestone]] Americas, Inc. *[[Continental Tire]] the Americas, LLC *[[Cooper Tire & Rubber Company]] *[[Kumho Tire]] U.S.A., Inc. *the [[Goodyear Tire & Rubber Company]] *[[Michelin]] North America, Inc. *[[Pirelli]] Tire North America *[[Sumitomo Rubber Industries|Sumitomo Rubber]] North America, Inc. *[[Toyo Tire & Rubber Company|Toyo]] Tire Holdings of Americas Inc. *[[Yokohama Tire]] Corporation.
==British Rubber Manufacturers' Association== The British Rubber Manufacturers' Association is another trade group that "represents the rubber manufacturing industry in the United Kingdom."<ref>{{cite book | last=Limited | first=Rapra Technology | title=Toxicity and Safe Handling of Rubber Chemicals | publisher=RAPRA Technology | year=1999 | isbn=978-1-85957-174-3 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-LVwSUhgJdoC&pg=PA462 | accessdate=July 30, 2016 | page=462}}</ref> It is based in London, England.<ref>{{cite book | last=King | first=R.W. | last2=Magid | first2=J. | title=Industrial Hazard and Safety Handbook: (Revised impression) | publisher=Elsevier Science | year=2013 | isbn=978-1-4831-0219-1 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tMj8BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA798 | accessdate=July 30, 2016 | page=798}}</ref>
